    slug: "islamic-rulings-on-menstruation-and-postpartum",
    description: `Islamic Rulings on Menstruation and Postpartum is an English-language Islamic jurisprudence book that provides a detailed and authoritative treatment of the legal rulings (ahkam) related to menstruation (hayd) and postpartum bleeding (nifas) as understood in the Islamic legal tradition. These topics are among the most important yet frequently misunderstood areas of Islamic law, as they directly affect a Muslim woman's ability to perform her daily prayers, observe the Ramadan fast, recite the Quran, engage in sexual relations with her husband, and fulfill other religious obligations. The book serves as an essential reference for Muslim women who need to understand these rulings in order to practice their faith correctly, as well as for Islamic scholars, students of fiqh, and anyone involved in providing religious education or counseling to Muslim women.

The book is organized into clear sections that address every major aspect of the legal rulings related to menstruation and postpartum bleeding. The first section defines the fundamental concepts, distinguishing between the three types of bleeding that Islamic law recognizes: menstruation (hayd), postpartum bleeding (nifas), and irregular bleeding (istihadah). For each type, the book provides the precise definition according to Islamic jurisprudence, including the minimum and maximum durations, the characteristics that distinguish one type from another, and the specific legal consequences that apply in each case. The rulings are presented with full references to the Quranic verses, hadith narrations, and scholarly opinions that form the basis of the Islamic legal position on each issue, allowing readers to understand not only what the ruling is but also the evidentiary basis upon which it is established.

The practical sections of the book address the specific acts of worship and daily activities that are affected by menstruation and postpartum bleeding. The book provides detailed guidance on prayer (salah), explaining that a woman is not required to perform the obligatory prayers during her menstrual period, the obligation to make up the missed prayers after the bleeding ends (addressing the scholarly difference of opinion on this issue), and the proper method of performing ghusl (the purificatory bath) that is required before resuming prayer. The section on fasting explains the obligation to make up any missed days of Ramadan fasting, the permissibility of fasting voluntary fasts after the bleeding has ended, and the scholarly discussion regarding whether a woman should attempt to fast during Ramadan if she experiences breakthrough bleeding. Additional sections cover the rules regarding recitation and touching of the Quran, entering the mosque, performing tawaf (circumambulation of the Kaaba), sexual relations with the husband, and the process of establishing regular menstrual cycles for legal purposes. The English prose is precise and well-organized, with Arabic terminology clearly explained, making this book an indispensable reference for every Muslim woman and a valuable addition to the English Islamic jurisprudence literature.`,
